<p style="font-size:8pt;padding-left:40px">(Listen Here 5:05 min)</p>
<p class="MsoNormal" align="center"><strong>Part Two &#8211; The Death Question</strong></p>
<p>Section 102 of the internal revenue code says that an heir  (beneficiary who inherits property) that receives property as a â€œgift, bequest,  devise, or inheritanceâ€ takes that property tax-free.Â  It states â€œGross income does not include the  value of property acquired by gift, bequest, devise, or inheritanceâ€.</p>
<p>You can read Section 102 at: <a href="http://www2.law.cornell.edu/uscode/html/uscode26/usc_sec_26_00000102----000-.html">http://www2.law.cornell.edu/uscode/html/uscode26/usc_sec_26_00000102&#8212;-000-.html</a></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Basis of an Heir</strong></p>
<p>The question then becomes, what if your heir then sells the  property that they received as an â€œinheritanceâ€ from you? What is the heirâ€™s  basis for calculating his or her gain?Â   Will the heir have any tax liability?</p>
<p>At present, Section 1014 of the internal revenue code allows  your heirs to take your property with a â€œstepped up basisâ€ [roughly Fair Market  Value (FMV)] of the property at the time of your death) so they would not  necessarily take over your low basis in the property.Â  However, the tax code in this area may  change, so you need to talk about this with your CPA or your accountant.Â  Under current Section 1014(a) the general  rule applied to property an heir receives from a decedent is that the heir&#039;s  basis equals the fair market value of the property at the time the decedent  dies.Â  Because of Section 1014, any  appreciation of the affected property that occurred during the decedent&#039;s  lifetime may never be taxed. The current operation of this code section  provides an incentive for taxpayers to defer taxes throughout oneâ€™s lifetime  until death.Â  One strategy that people  refer to with 1031 exchanges is called â€œDefer, Defer, Defer,â€¦Dieâ€.Â  The idea is that one never recognizes any  gains during oneâ€™s lifetime, but instead continually defers the recognition of  gain (compounding and building wealth tax-free) until they die.</p>
<p>Section 1014(f) says that this section shall not apply to  decedents who die after December 31, 2009.Â   This â€œsunset provisionâ€ came from the Economic Growth and Tax Relief  Reconciliation Act of 2001 (EGTRRA).Â   According to EGTRRA, Section 1014 will be terminated. EGTRRA replaces  Section 1014 with a modified â€œcarryover basisâ€ rule, under which the property  will receive a basis equal to the lesser of the adjusted basis of the property  in the hands of the decedent, or the fair market value of the property on the  date of the decedent&#039;s death. So, your heirs would probably take over your low  basis, and they would need to continue to defer the taxes by utilizing 1031 tax  exchanges. The good news is that they could also continue the strategy of  â€œDeferring, Deferring,Â  Deferring,â€¦Dyingâ€â€¦  generation after generation.</p>
<p>You can read Section 1014 at <a href="http://www2.law.cornell.edu/uscode/html/uscode26/usc_sec_26_00001014----000-.html">http://www2.law.cornell.edu/uscode/html/uscode26/usc_sec_26_00001014&#8212;-000-.html</a></p>
